  "method": "Build a circuit-aware, mixed-precision quantization pipeline that first locates in-context learning (ICL) and chain-of-thought (CoT) critical substructures, then allocates precision and learns small corrective scalings specifically to preserve them. Start with a probing suite of ICL/CoT prompts (e.g., induction/copy tasks, few-shot function learning, GSM8K with rationales). On the full-precision model, compute per-head and per-MLP-neuron importance by (i) ablation delta-loss (zeroing a head/neuron’s output), (ii) gradient-based saliency on attention logits and MLP activations with respect to next-token loss under ICL prompts, and (iii) activation statistics that flag outlier channels during these prompts. Aggregate these into a protection score and tag the top bands of attention heads (often induction/copy heads, delimiter-bridging heads) and MLP channels as protected. Keep a light-weight runtime saliency signal (e.g., head-wise attentivity to instruction/BOS tokens) to optionally gate a small extra-precision budget per input.\n\nQuantize with module- and channel-granularity mixed precision: weights in non-critical paths use 3–4 bits per-channel/group-wise affine quantization; protected heads/channels and all attention softmax logits use 8–16 bits. For attention, keep Q and attention logits in higher precision; quantize K/V caches to 8 bits with per-head/group scales. Before activation quantization, learn per-channel refinement factors that tame activation outliers and fold these scalings into adjacent weights so the deployed graph still uses standard integer quantization. Use stochastic rounding and per-group clipping calibrated on ICL/CoT prompts; set stricter clip ranges on salient tokens while allowing looser ranges on low-saliency tokens to limit error where it matters.\n\nRun a brief quantization-aware tuning phase that explicitly preserves ICL/CoT behavior. During forward passes, randomly substitute a proportion r of hidden states with their quantized counterparts and compute: (a) a distillation loss on logits toward the full-precision teacher over ICL/CoT prompt distributions, (b) an attention-map alignment loss on protected heads to match teacher patterns, and (c) a lightweight contrastive alignment between teacher and student intermediate representations so that prompt/rationale pairs remain closer than mismatched pairs, reducing semantic drift under quantization. Gradually increase r and quantization aggressiveness over training.\n\nUse a curriculum over context length and task complexity: begin with short-range induction and simple few-shot tasks, then scale to longer contexts and multi-step CoT reasoning. Optionally, in deeper layers only, apply very light attentivity-guided token sparsification on low-saliency tokens (never on rationale or delimiter-adjacent tokens) to curb activation outliers and further stabilize activation quantization without harming long-range reasoning. Validate with head ablations post-quantization to confirm protected circuits retain their influence, and report both perplexity and ICL/CoT benchmarks to ensure the targets were preserved.",
  "rationale": "Emergent abilities rely on a small set of specialized attention heads and MLP channels (e.g., induction/copy circuits). Uniform low-bit quantization disproportionately harms them because these components produce outlier activations and govern long-range dependencies. By first identifying and then protecting these substructures with mixed precision and learned per-channel scalings, we concentrate the limited high-precision budget where it most affects ICL/CoT while still reaping large memory and speed gains elsewhere.\n\nQuantization-aware tuning that mixes quantized activations into training and aligns student–teacher attention and representations on ICL/CoT prompts directly pressures the quantized model to encode the structures that support these abilities. A length/complexity curriculum makes the student robust to long-horizon accumulation of quantization noise. Together, the circuit-aware precision allocation, activation outlier refinement, and targeted QAT preserve emergent behaviors even at low bitwidths.",
