  "method": "Ability-aware mixed-precision quantization proceeds in three stages: attribute, allocate, and adapt. First, we build an ability attribution map for in-context learning (ICL) and chain-of-thought (CoT). On a curated set of ICL/CoT prompts, we run a full-precision teacher to collect activations and outcomes on tasks that reflect emergent abilities (e.g., few-shot composition, induction heads, multi-step reasoning). We insert structured gates on heads and MLP channel groups and perform a short quantization-aware fine-tune with a sparsity penalty; components that cannot be suppressed without harming ICL/CoT accuracy receive high gate scores, yielding a ranked list of critical heads/channels per layer. In parallel, we train a tiny selector that reads layer-wise summaries (e.g., attention entropies, token-wise hidden states) and predicts which tokens/positions and which attention heads constitute the core reasoning pathway for a given prompt, producing per-token masks. A quick layer-wise probing pass corroborates that later decoder layers and specific attention projections contribute disproportionately to ICL/CoT, seeding an informative prior for downstream allocation.\n\nGiven a global bit budget, we construct a static precision plan by progressive promotion. We start from a strong baseline (e.g., W4A4 with per-channel symmetric weight quantization and per-group activation quantization), keep numerically fragile ops in higher precision by default (layer norm/RMSNorm, rotary embeddings, softmax, logits), and then iteratively promote the highest-ranked components to 8–16 bits until the budget is met. Promotion is decided by estimated marginal gain-per-bit computed on the ICL/CoT validation set: attention K/V and output projections in mid-to-late layers, and narrow MLP bottlenecks on reasoning-critical layers are typical beneficiaries. Activation ranges are calibrated on CoT-heavy traces, with per-token or small-group scales for attention blocks that carry reasoning tokens; the KV cache is kept at minimally 8-bit (or fp16 for promoted heads). Optionally, we insert tiny residual adapters (e.g., low-rank) only along the protected paths and keep these in higher precision to restore expressivity lost to quantization without inflating the overall memory footprint.\n\nAt inference, we adapt precision on the fly with a lightweight uncertainty head and the learned selector. A deterministic uncertainty estimator operating on pre-logit/attention statistics produces per-token confidence, which we fuse with the selector’s mask to detect CoT spans and moments of high epistemic demand. For tokens/heads flagged as critical or uncertain, we route matmuls through a higher-precision kernel for the promoted components (or temporarily dequantize activations for those heads/MLP groups), while the remainder continues with low-bit kernels; batching tokens by precision tier preserves throughput. This realizes token- and head-specific mixed precision: most of the sequence runs at low cost, while the model “spends” precision exactly where reasoning circuits are active.\n\nTraining uses quantization-aware fine-tuning with a scaffolded bit-width curriculum and explicit ability preservation. We begin from fp16/bf16, distill logits and intermediate features on ICL/CoT tasks, then progressively lower bit-widths and expand the set of quantized components, re-evaluating the gating ranks as we go. The objective combines standard LM loss with auxiliary losses that reward correct few-shot adaptation and multi-step CoT consistency from a full-precision teacher; we avoid self-evaluation signals and track external, reference-based ability metrics to steer optimization. A final calibration pass refreshes activation scales on CoT traces and freezes the selector and uncertainty head, yielding a deployable model with static promotions plus dynamic, token-aware precision routing.",
  "rationale": "Emergent abilities are carried by sparse, compositional circuits (e.g., specific heads, late-layer MLP paths, and token-time slices during scratchpad reasoning). Uniform low-bit quantization maintains average-token likelihoods (perplexity) but injects noise into precisely these narrow pathways, disproportionately harming ICL/CoT. By first attributing where these abilities live, then statically promoting the most consequential components, we prevent large, localized error amplification while still quantizing the bulk of parameters and activations.\n\nDynamic, token-aware precision further limits cost by only elevating precision when the model is actively reasoning (as detected by a selector and uncertainty head), keeping the typical forward pass cheap while preserving reliability on hard steps. A scaffolded quantization curriculum with distillation preserves these behaviors as precision drops, and evaluating against external, task-grounded ability metrics ensures we optimize for the real objective rather than a proxy like perplexity or self-judged fluency.",
